The Bulk Edit screen in JIRA Agile has a text note below the "Change Sprint" field that reads:
{quote}
Sprint field for GreenHopper use only
{quote}

This should be updated to "JIRA Agile".

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-9955].
  {panel}

In an agile board, under "Filter", "Saved Filter", I can left-click to select a saved filter.
However, this dropdown is limited to 20 entries, with no scrolling (see attachment).
I you want to see the 21st entry, you need to know the filter's name, and start typing.

*Rating*: :D Awesome!

{panel:title=What do you like?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#c2ffa2|bgColor=#fff}
No need GreenHopper with all its stuff (fields, entities, etc.) - just simple work in JIRA as you do before and enjoy real burndown chart with no extra effort.
Great job! Thank you guys.
{panel}

{panel:title=What needs to be improved?|borderColor=#ccc| titleBGColor=#faacad|bgColor=#fff}
It would be nice to have 
* a burndown chart for tasks along with efforts burndown;
* a time frame frozen for some recurrent period (like 1 week, 2 weeks, etc. or may be days...) starting from a particular day
{panel}

*Reporter*: Alexander Kashtalyan
*E-mail*: [mailto:akashtalyan@artezio.com]

h3. Steps to reproduce:

# Create multiple swim lanes;
#- Be sure that some of the swim lanes are smaller than others, just like in the screenshot;
# Try to move an issue to a column which you can choose multiple status ("Done" column for example where you would choose either "Resolved" or "Closed")

h3. Current Behaviour:

You will see that you will only be able to perform the transition on top if you hold the issue by the top of it or move to the bottom transition if you hold it by the bottom part;

h3. Expected behaviour;

Have the possibility of moving the issues to any desired status.

When trying to get the details of an issue through the REST API the response for the Sprint looks something like this:

{code:javascript}
customfield_10007:[
"com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint@a29f07[rapidViewId=<null>,state=CLOSED,name=NORD - Sprint 42,startDate=2013-07-29T06:47:00.000+02:00,endDate=2013-08-11T20:47:00.000+02:00,completeDate=2013-08-14T15:31:33.157+02:00,id=107]",
"com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint@769133[rapidViewId=<null>,state=ACTIVE,name=NORD - Sprint 43,startDate=2013-08-14T15:32:47.322+02:00,endDate=2013-08-23T15:32:47.322+02:00,completeDate=<null>,id=117]"
],
{code}
It looks like toString of the Sprint class which isn't very easy to parse/read with an application. Is their a way to simple get the Sprint Name or id returned through the REST API. It's necessary to be able to retrieve the Sprint value in an internal tool for our QA Team (Spira Test).

On the other side, using toString in the REST API output doesn't seem like a good idea to me ...

Current state of Sprint after it is completed, you cannot alter the naming of it. Based on the use case provided by customer:

{quote}
Basically it amounts to the fact that when you start a new project naming conventions are not really something you have fully stabilized. When at a later point in the project you want to refit some of your older works to the now more stable conventions it would be nice to be allowed to do this.

In this specific case sprint naming should follow a convention which will allow us to use the api more fluently without taking in to account to many obscure ways of naming sprints.
{quote}

This feature will be good to have in the target of re-organizing things and to be identified more fluently by the api.

h3. Symptoms

{code}
@4000000052497be016a77234 2013-09-30 06:25:42,378 TP-Processor12 ERROR sysadmin 385x976x1 1dm2fuh 59.167.133.100,131.103.27.4 /rest/plugins/1.0/com.pyxis.greenhopper.jira-key [sal.core.upgrade.PluginUpgrader] Upgrade failed: null
@4000000052497be016a77dec java.lang.NullPointerException
@4000000052497be016a77dec       at com.atlassian.greenhopper.upgrade.GhUpgradeTask040.findAndUpdateOptions(GhUpgradeTask040.java:190)
@4000000052497be016a781d4       at com.atlassian.greenhopper.upgrade.GhUpgradeTask040.updateEpicStatusOptions(GhUpgradeTask040.java:162)
@4000000052497be016a8a6cc       at com.atlassian.greenhopper.upgrade.GhUpgradeTask040.performUpgrade(GhUpgradeTask040.java:93)
@4000000052497be016a8aab4       at com.atlassian.greenhopper.upgrade.AbstractGhUpgradeTask.doUpgrade(AbstractGhUpgradeTask.java:62)
@4000000052497be016a8aab4       at sun.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method)
@4000000052497be016a8ae9c       at sun.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:39)
@4000000052497be016a8c9f4       at sun.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:25)
@4000000052497be016a8cddc       at java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:597)
{code}

h3. Cause

The cause of this issue is that the *Epic Status* field is not configured correctly. Specifically, the field is expected to be configured with only one custom field context, which applies to issues in All Projects, with issue type Epic.

If the field is configured with one context which selects specific projects and issue type Epic, the upgrade task will fail.

h3. Work around

If the Epic Status field is in this configured state, it should not be "locked" (as it is a non-standard configuration). Therefore it should be possible to amend the configuration as follows:

# View all Custom Fields
# Find Epic Status and choose Configure
# Find the default custom field context (there should be only one) and Edit it
# At the bottom of the screen, under projects, choose Global Projects instead of selecting specific projects.
# Disable and re-enable the JIRA Agile plugin
# Re-indexing the instance

The upgrade task should then succeed, and JIRA Agile functionality will be restored. This however may have the side effect of locking the Epic Status field from further updates. However, the initial configuration of the custom field context selecting specific projects is unsupported.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Software Server*. Using *JIRA Software Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSWCLOUD-9886].
  {panel}

To facilitate our Agile workflow we have both an active open sprint and a "next" sprint which has not yet been started.  Adding tickets to the "next" sprint via the web UI works fine, but I would like to be able to add tickets to this sprint via REST for some internal tools.

Currently, the "next" sprint does not show up in results for sprints/rapid_view_id. Attempting to guess the sprint ID (incrementing the ID of the open sprint) and attempting to add the ticket using sprint/sprint_id/issues/add yields a "Sprint does not exist" error.
